      "writtenOn": "2015-09-02T16:24:51Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That\u0027s right, this is not clear. Essentially you call android::base::ThreadLooper::get() to retrieve the android::base::Looper instance for the current thread, by default, this creates a new \u0027generic\u0027 looper based on select().\n\nBut alternatively, you can create and android::qemu::Looper instance and inject it into the (main) thread with android::base::ThreadLooper::set()\n\nThis way, any code that uses ThreadLooper::get() will use the QEMU-based main loop when it runs in the main thread, even if it doesn\u0027t know anything about QEMU.\n\nThat\u0027s the kind of decoupling I\u0027m looking for in our code, but I need a better way to explain that.",
      "parentUuid": "045f8228_9117bbdc",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 33,
        "endLine": 92,
        "endChar": 15
      },
      "revId": "de87a03ab9bb7d18ca92468a78265c98d48be186",
